(version 1)
;; ===========================================================================================
;; @piflow/core SeatbeltSandbox READ-SCOPE profile -- macOS Seatbelt (sandbox-exec).
;;
;; This is the @piflow/core port of templates/pi-runner/sandbox/read-scope.sb. The SeatbeltSandbox
;; provider (sandbox/seatbelt.ts buildSandboxProfile) renders a per-exec copy of this template with
;; the home, tmpdir, and declared-scope tokens substituted, then runs sandbox-exec -f <copy> sh -c <cmd>.
;;
;; Two hard rules for editing this file (DO NOT BREAK THEM):
;;   1. Comments are PURE ASCII. The SBPL/TinyScheme reader miscounts multibyte UTF-8 (em-dashes,
;;      ellipses) and then parses comment text as code (an "unbound variable" error).
;;   2. NEVER write a driver placeholder token in a comment. The provider string-substitutes those
;;      tokens; a multi-line scope value spilled into a comment becomes live code and breaks parsing.
;;      Each token below appears ONCE, only at its rule site.
;;
;; WHY: a non-Claude model ignores a prompt-level READING LAW and spelunks files outside its lane (it
;; grepped the whole repo for a phantom component and read other units source, bloating context, then
;; stalled). Prompt rules are unenforceable on weak models, so the scope boundary must live in the OS.
;; Seatbelt is kernel-enforced, INHERITS to every child process (so a spawned grep/find/cat is bound
;; too) and cannot be lifted from inside the sandbox.
;;
;; POLICY: allow everything EXCEPT file reads AND file writes; deny ALL file reads, deny ALL file writes;
;; then re-allow exactly (1) the toolchain/system roots a node + node + npm need to run/scratch and (2)
;; the per-exec DECLARED scope the provider injects below. A read OR write of the wider tree (another
;; unit, a sibling node dir, ~/.ssh, the repo at large) returns Operation-not-permitted, while the
;; workdir, the declared scope, and node_modules read+write fine.
;;
;; SCOPE: reads AND writes (symmetric jail). exec (process-exec*/process-fork) and network are left open
;; (allow default) so the toolchain runs unaffected -- the `pi` agent MUST run tools (node/git/scripts)
;; and reach its model gateway. ONLY file-read*/file-write* are the boundary.
;;
;; WRITABLE SET: the toolchain write-scratch roots below are adopted from OpenAI's Codex CLI macOS
;; Seatbelt workspace-write profile (codex-rs/sandboxing/src/seatbelt_base_policy.sbpl + the writable-root
;; build in protocol.rs get_writable_roots_with_cwd: cwd, /tmp, $TMPDIR, and the /dev/null write literal)
;; rather than invented -- a battle-tested set, generous enough that node/npm/git scratch is never EPERMd.
;; We add piflow's home scratch (~/.npm ~/.cache ~/.pi ~/.piflow ~/.config) so pi can write its own state.
;; ===========================================================================================

(allow default)

;; Deny every file read up front, then immediately re-allow METADATA everywhere (last match wins).
;; Metadata = stat/traverse, which the toolchain needs to resolve paths (node getcwd / dyld); denying
;; it EPERMs uv_cwd and node never boots. DATA (content) stays denied globally and is re-granted only
;; for the scoped subpaths below -- and content is exactly what a wandering read leaks: cat/grep read
;; file data, ls/find readdir reads directory data, so both stay blocked for out-of-scope paths.
(deny file-read*)
(allow file-read-metadata)

;; --- toolchain / system roots: node, npm, the dyld shared cache, temp ---
(allow file-read*
  (subpath "/usr")
  (subpath "/bin")
  (subpath "/sbin")
  (subpath "/System")
  (subpath "/Library")
  (subpath "/opt")
  (subpath "/private/var")
  (subpath "/private/tmp")
  (subpath "/private/etc")
  (subpath "/dev")
  (subpath "@TMPDIR@")
  (subpath "@HOME@/.pi")
  (subpath "@HOME@/.piflow")
  (subpath "@HOME@/.npm")
  (subpath "@HOME@/.cache")
  (subpath "@HOME@/.config")
  (subpath "@HOME@/.nvm")
  (literal "/")
  (literal "/etc")
  (literal "/tmp")
  (literal "/var"))

;; --- per-exec DECLARED read scope (provider-injected from CreateOpts.readScope + the workdir) ---
;; the node's workdir + its declared read roots + node_modules. Anything not listed here (sibling
;; units, other out dirs, the wider repo) stays denied.
(allow file-read*
@SCOPE_ALLOWS@)

;; ===========================================================================================
;; WRITE SCOPE -- symmetric to the read jail above. Deny EVERY file write up front, then re-allow only
;; (1) the toolchain write-scratch roots (Codex-derived: see WRITABLE SET in the header) and (2) the
;; per-exec DECLARED write scope (workdir + CreateOpts.writeScope == the node's owns). A write to a
;; sibling node dir, ~/.ssh, ~/Documents, or the repo at large returns Operation-not-permitted -- and
;; because Seatbelt inherits to every child, a `bash echo > /anywhere` is bounded too.
(deny file-write*)

;; --- toolchain / system write-scratch roots (Codex workspace-write writable set + piflow home state) ---
;; Generous on PURPOSE: bounding the blast radius (no writes to $HOME-sensitive paths, sibling dirs, the
;; repo at large), NOT maximal tightness. An EPERM on the toolchain's OWN scratch breaks node/pi and is a
;; worse failure than no jail. /dev/null|stdout|stderr|fd are how the shell redirects; /private/var holds
;; the per-user $TMPDIR (var/folders/...) and caches; /tmp + $TMPDIR are the canonical scratch dirs.
(allow file-write*
  (subpath "@TMPDIR@")
  (subpath "/private/tmp")
  (subpath "/private/var/folders")
  (subpath "@HOME@/.pi")
  (subpath "@HOME@/.piflow")
  (subpath "@HOME@/.npm")
  (subpath "@HOME@/.cache")
  (subpath "@HOME@/.config")
  (literal "/dev/null")
  (literal "/dev/zero")
  (literal "/dev/stdout")
  (literal "/dev/stderr")
  (literal "/dev/tty")
  (subpath "/dev/fd")
  (literal "/tmp")
  (subpath "/private/var/tmp"))

;; --- per-exec DECLARED write scope (provider-injected from CreateOpts.writeScope + the workdir) ---
;; the node's workdir (its deliverable tree) + its declared write roots (owns). Anything not listed here
;; (sibling units, other out dirs, the wider repo, $HOME) stays denied.
(allow file-write*
@WRITE_SCOPE_ALLOWS@)
